As my local pool hall, I have a high regard for this place. The staff is welcoming. The food is better than one would initially give credit, having not tried it. Don't assume it's low grade bar food because it's not.  The pool tables are well taken care of and at an affordable hourly rate. I love this place - anyone looking for good vibes and billiards, check out City Pool Hall.

✍️  I play here occasionally when I am in Chicago. Most of the time I go to Chris’ up the street on North Milwaukee Ave. Last Thanksgiving I went to Surge for the first time. In my opinion and experience, comparatively, CPH is a small poolroom and pool tables are a bit too close together for my taste. But, tables are well maintained.  Last time I was at CPH was in 2017 on an APA league night. All the tables were tied up with league play but I enjoyed myself eating, drinking and watching matches. League players were friendly and easy to talk with. Food and service were great compared to what I endure in pool rooms where I live in Northern Virginia. Tables in NOVA are generally dirty and in poor repair. Lighting is awful, food mediocre, service is surly and in general poolroom owners and staff are outright contemptuous to customers. You think I am exaggerating, I assure you I am not. Be happy that you are a pool player in Chicago with many great options. I think CPH is one of them.

I have been here at least 15-20 times and I really loved playing pool here. They always hold a credit card on file when you shoot pool, which is normal at most pool halls that I've been to. Last week after finishing my usual 2 hour pool session with my buddy, I go to pay the tab with my credit card thats on file behind the desk. These clowns gave my credit card to the wrong customer! My card wasn't charged because the customers who were given my card had payed with a different card. I guess they put my card away without catching the mistake, which led to their card being left at the pool hall. How hard is it to check and ask for a customer's name before you give the credit card back?! It literally takes 2 seconds to do that. So now we have 2 problems, my card being missing and these poor souls walking around not knowing the pool hall had theirs.  The part that angered me the most was how the employees handled it. At first I was calm but I became frustrated when the "manager" wasn't proactive about the situation.Two employees spoke to him about this and he stood about 15 feet away from me, knowing we had an issue and never came to confront me about the situation. He disappeared behind the bar and left this poor waitress to deal with this situation. She was very apologetic and tried to Facebook message the person who left their card. She then told me she was "trying to help me", which was the final straw for me. Like how the hell are you trying to "help me" when YOU were the one that gave my card away?! After that happened I insisted to speak to a manager and he finally comes out from hiding. This guy tells me that I still have time to catch the people with my credit card because the people who had it went to Punch Bowl Social to retrieve a phone that they had left (I also heard them say that when they were walking out). No apologies from this dude or nothing, like it was no big deal. I went to punch bowl social and tried to tried to look for 2 Indian dudes hanging out with a white girl, the people that were across the pool hall from me that I had caught a quick glimpse of earlier in the night. I was unsuccessful and very frustrated so I just called the credit card company and cancelled it. It was annoying switching all the accounts that I had linked to the credit card. I will never ever go back to this joint. These clowns will miss out on a few hundred bucks a month that I usually spent there.  Luckily, there are other pool hall in the area. Two lessons to learn from this unfortunate situation. Never go to a place that doesn't know how to safely handle your credit card and never go to Punch Bowl Social looking for 2 Indians and a white girl. There were a lot.

Great place to play pool with the boys ($15 buckets of beers during Blackhawks and Cubs games) or to play some serious pool competition.

In town on business and brought my brother (16) with me to give him exposure to my work and the city of Chicago. We enjoy to play pool together so came to City Pool Hall for dinner and to play.  No one greeted us as we came in. The server finally came over and said “Can I help you?” Very appropriate greeting (smh).  Let’s chat about my issue: There are no posted signs that says 21 and up nor anyone to greet you at the door to check id’s. They refused the let us play because he was under age. We were okay with that and figured we’d eat since we took an Uber all the way over here. I attempted to order a beer but was then told that I couldn’t order a beer because I was in the company of a minor. Please explain?!?! I’m certain I’m older than the server. Need I say, we didn’t get to eat there— though I’m sure they didn’t care.  I don’t want to believe this was form of racism or discrimination but I’m having a hard time believing that.  Do better!
